I actually think this is a nice refinement of your interface theory.

The interface isn’t valuable because it looks like something.

It’s valuable because it imports an entire package of useful constraints and behaviors from another domain.

So perhaps the Pantheon doesn’t ask:

“Which metaphor is coolest?”

It asks:

“Which morphology imports the operator set I need?”

That’s a much more systematic way to choose interfaces. Instead of decorating an idea with an animal, person, or machine, you’re deliberately selecting the source domain whose behaviors best transfer to the target problem. That turns metaphor into a design decision rather than just a stylistic one.